          "front": "hungry",
          "back": "جائع",
          "romanized": "ja'i'",
          "grammarNote": "Arabic expresses hunger and thirst with adjectives directly: أنا جائع (ana ja'i' = I am hungry), أنا عطشان (ana atshan = I am thirsty). Unlike Spanish which uses 'tener' (to have hunger), Arabic simply places the adjective as a predicate with no verb. Feminine forms: جائعة (ja'i'a), عطشانة (atshanah)."
        },
        {
          "front": "I'm hungry. Are you thirsty?",
          "back": "أنا جائع. هل أنت عطشان؟",
          "romanized": "ana ja'i'. hal anta atshan?"
